00:17:21,407 --> 00:17:24,035
of covert aggression
of some kind.

230
00:17:24,143 --> 00:17:26,941
The kind of view that enabled you
to think of the conflict...

231
00:17:27,046 --> 00:17:29,014
<i>in, really, World War II terms.</i>

232
00:17:29,114 --> 00:17:31,014
<i>That was an unquestioned assumption.</i>

233
00:17:31,116 --> 00:17:33,516
It had an idealistic flavor to it,

234
00:17:33,619 --> 00:17:37,453
but it was the underpinning of
an imperial policy, basically.

235
00:17:37,556 --> 00:17:40,423
I shared the assumption,
very easily,

236
00:17:40,526 --> 00:17:42,790
and felt it as an idealistic one really.

237
00:17:42,895 --> 00:17:44,795
We were doing something for them.

238
00:17:44,897 --> 00:17:48,594
I recall that I was in the New York area
at the time,

239
00:17:48,700 --> 00:17:51,100
and I stopped by
to see General MacArthur,

240
00:17:51,203 --> 00:17:54,229
who I had known for several years.

241
00:17:55,874 --> 00:18:00,243
Uh, when he greeted me, he made, uh,
quite a prophetic statement.

242
00:18:01,580 --> 00:18:06,415
He said, ''Westmoreland,
I-I see you have a new job.''

243
00:18:07,986 --> 00:18:11,945
He said, ''I hope you appreciate
that this new assignment...

244
00:18:13,358 --> 00:18:17,590
is filled with opportunities,
but fraught with hazards.''

245
00:18:17,696 --> 00:18:21,598
And indeed, uh,
this was a prophetic statement.

246
00:18:42,087 --> 00:18:44,521
It can be described much like, uh...

247
00:18:44,623 --> 00:18:48,957
a-a-a singer doing an aria...

248
00:18:49,061 --> 00:18:52,724
that's totally into what he's doing,
you know, totally feeling it.

249
00:18:52,831 --> 00:18:55,561
He knows the aria,
and he's experiencing the aria.

250
00:18:55,667 --> 00:19:00,127
And he knows his limits, and he knows
whether he's doing it and doing it well.

251
00:19:00,239 --> 00:19:02,639
Flying an aircraft
can be a great deal like that.

252
00:19:02,741 --> 00:19:04,641
What's a race driver feel like?

253
00:19:04,743 --> 00:19:07,541
Why does a guy want to drive
in the Indianapolis 500?

254
00:19:07,646 --> 00:19:10,012
I guess, perhaps, the risk of dying,

255
00:19:10,115 --> 00:19:12,345
being killed is part of it
that makes it thrilling.

256
00:19:16,989 --> 00:19:20,618
<i>[ Floyd ] I can tell when the aircraft</i>
<i>feels right, when it's about to stall.</i>

257
00:19:20,726 --> 00:19:24,355
<i>I can tell when I can't</i>
<i>pull another fraction of a pound...</i>

258
00:19:24,463 --> 00:19:27,955
<i>or the airplane will stall,</i>
<i>flip out and spin on me.</i>

259
00:19:28,066 --> 00:19:31,092
I would follow a pathway on something
like a TV screen in front of me...

260
00:19:31,203 --> 00:19:33,637
that would direct me
right, left or center--

261
00:19:33,739 --> 00:19:36,867
follow the steering,
keep the steering symbol, uh, centered.

262
00:19:36,975 --> 00:19:40,433
I'd see a little attack light
when we'd stepped into attack.

263
00:19:40,546 --> 00:19:43,447
I could pull the ''commit'' switch
on my stick,

264
00:19:43,549 --> 00:19:45,517
and the computer took over.

265
00:19:45,617 --> 00:19:49,314
A computer figured out the ballistics,
the airspeed, the slant range...

266
00:19:49,421 --> 00:19:51,480
<i>and dropped the bombs</i>
<i>when we got to the appropriate point,</i>

267
00:19:51,590 --> 00:19:53,683
<i>in whichever kind of attack</i>
<i>we'd selected,</i>

268
00:19:53,792 --> 00:19:57,922
<i>whether it was flying straight and level</i>
<i>or tossing our bombs out.</i>

269
00:19:58,030 --> 00:20:01,727
So it was very much of
a technical expertise thing.

270
00:20:01,833 --> 00:20:04,996
I was a good pilot, you know.
I had, uh, uh,

271
00:20:05,103 --> 00:20:07,333
I had a lot of pride
in my ability to fly.

272
00:20:12,477 --> 00:20:15,037
You're up there
doing something that, uh,

273
00:20:15,147 --> 00:20:19,709
mankind has only dreamed of; the flying,
especially at night, in an aircraft.

274
00:20:19,818 --> 00:20:23,276
The A-6 is one of the few
that can really do it the way we did it.

275
00:20:23,388 --> 00:20:27,119
Um, a World War II aviator would not
even dream of doing the things we did.

276
00:20:27,226 --> 00:20:29,194
It's definitely
the ultimate in aviation.

277
00:20:42,541 --> 00:20:45,977
Almost everybody
has blown off firecrackers.

278
00:20:46,078 --> 00:20:49,138
<i>The thrill you get when you</i>
<i>see something explode as a child,</i>

279
00:20:49,248 --> 00:20:51,375
<i>or even as an adult almost.</i>

280
00:20:51,483 --> 00:20:54,384
You put something in the can
and watch the can blow up in the air.

281
00:21:00,692 --> 00:21:03,354
<i>And the excitement,</i>
<i>the sense of excitement,</i>

282
00:21:03,462 --> 00:21:06,454
<i>especially if you're getting shot at,</i>
<i>is just incredible.</i>

283
00:21:08,700 --> 00:21:10,998
You get there, have a real good mission,
hit your target,

284
00:21:11,103 --> 00:21:13,663
find out later your target
was totally destroyed,

285
00:21:13,772 --> 00:21:17,105
that it wasn't one of these misses
or almost, you got it.

286
00:21:17,209 --> 00:21:22,078
And come back and make a night carrier
landing recovery. Uh, that's fantastic.

287
00:21:22,180 --> 00:21:25,308
To say it's thrilling,
yes, it's deeply satisfying.

288
00:21:37,229 --> 00:21:39,322
[ Speaking Vietnamese ]

289
00:21:39,431 --> 00:21:42,195
-<i>[ Translator ] The planes again.</i>
-<i>[ Man #2 Speaking Vietnamese ]</i>

290
00:21:42,301 --> 00:21:46,169
<i>[ Translator #2 ]</i>
<i>Are they American or Vietnamese?</i>

291
00:21:46,271 --> 00:21:50,435
<i>[ Translator #1 ] I don't know</i>
<i>whose they are.Just airplanes.</i>

292
00:21:53,945 --> 00:21:56,505
<i>[ Translator #2 ]</i>
<i>What was this here?</i>

293
00:21:56,615 --> 00:21:59,175
<i>[ Translator #1 ]</i>
<i>I used to raise pigs here, right there.</i>

294
00:21:59,284 --> 00:22:01,650
<i>[ Man #2 Speaking Vietnamese ]</i>

295
00:22:01,753 --> 00:22:06,349
<i>[ Translator #2 ]</i>
<i>Where was the kitchen?</i>

296
00:22:10,195 --> 00:22:12,993
<i>[ Translator #1 ] The kitchen was here.</i>
<i>They built it with bricks.</i>

297
00:22:13,098 --> 00:22:16,158
<i>This was the floor.</i>
<i>And this was for the heat.</i>

298
00:22:16,268 --> 00:22:18,828
<i>[ Translator #2 ]</i>
<i>What's that?</i>

299
00:22:18,937 --> 00:22:20,928
<i>[ Translator #1 ]</i>
<i>That is the bomb crater.</i>

300
00:22:21,039 --> 00:22:24,475
<i>The bombs dropped there</i>
<i>and destroyed everything I had.</i>

301
00:22:25,877 --> 00:22:29,677
<i>[ Speaking Vietnamese ]</i>

302
00:22:29,781 --> 00:22:34,218
<i>[ Translator ] An older sister died,</i>
<i>and I've another older sister left.</i>

303
00:22:34,319 --> 00:22:37,311
<i>Yes, there were just the three of us.</i>
<i>But then one died.</i>

304
00:22:37,422 --> 00:22:40,585
<i>And I'm supposed to live</i>
<i>in a house over there.</i>

305
00:22:42,461 --> 00:22:45,362
<i>But now it's just a heap of rubble.</i>
-<i>[ Man Speaking Vietnamese ]</i>

306
00:22:45,464 --> 00:22:49,696
<i>[ Translator #2 ]</i>
<i>How old was your sister?</i>

307
00:22:49,801 --> 00:22:52,167
<i>[ Translator #1 ]</i>
<i>Seventy-eight.</i>

308
00:22:52,270 --> 00:22:55,671
<i>[ Translator #2 ]</i>
<i>What did she die of?.</i>

309
00:22:55,774 --> 00:22:58,334
<i>[ Translator #1 ] Bombs.</i>
<i>Bombs were dropped here the other day,</i>

310
00:22:58,443 --> 00:23:00,411
<i>and they killed her.</i>

311
00:23:00,512 --> 00:23:03,481
<i>[Jet Passing Overhead ]</i>

312
00:23:06,385 --> 00:23:10,116
[ Speaking Vietnamese ]

313
00:23:10,222 --> 00:23:12,281
<i>[ Translator ]</i>
<i>I'm so unhappy.</i>

314
00:23:21,366 --> 00:23:24,335
<i>My sister died</i>
<i>and I've got no home left.</i>

315
00:23:24,436 --> 00:23:26,836
<i>I've moved in</i>
<i>with my sister here.</i>

316
00:23:29,741 --> 00:23:31,709
<i>I've been wounded.</i>

317
00:23:34,379 --> 00:23:39,078
<i>I can't do anything for a living now.</i>
<i>I'm old and weak.</i>

318
00:23:39,184 --> 00:23:43,587
<i>I've got nothing to sell.</i>
<i>Nothing to do.</i>

319
00:24:09,481 --> 00:24:11,540
Mm.

320
00:24:13,852 --> 00:24:16,912
<i>[Jet Passing Overhead ]</i>

321
00:24:17,022 --> 00:24:19,422
<i>[ Coker ] You really just</i>
<i>don't have time for personal thoughts...</i>

322
00:24:19,524 --> 00:24:22,960
<i>when you're up there flying around</i>
<i>at 500, 600 miles an hours.</i>

323
00:24:23,061 --> 00:24:25,427
<i>You might call it an electronic war</i>
<i>in a certain way.</i>

324
00:24:25,530 --> 00:24:27,657
<i>I didn't have time to think</i>
<i>about anything else.</i>

325
00:24:27,766 --> 00:24:30,997
If you wanted to later, you might.
But it was all business.

326
00:24:31,102 --> 00:24:33,400
It's, um,just strictly professionalism.

327
00:24:33,505 --> 00:24:35,837
We had a job to do
and we did it.

328
00:24:35,941 --> 00:24:39,069
Never could see the people.
You never could see--

329
00:24:39,177 --> 00:24:42,203
Occasionally you saw the houses when
you were bombing around a village...

330
00:24:42,314 --> 00:24:44,373
or bombing in a village.

331
00:24:44,483 --> 00:24:46,747
Uh, you never
heard the explosion.

332
00:24:46,852 --> 00:24:50,185
You never saw any blood or any screams.
It was very clean.

333
00:24:50,288 --> 00:24:53,519
-<i>[ Floyd ] You're doing a job.</i>
- [ Speaking Vietnamese ]

334
00:24:53,625 --> 00:24:55,991
<i>You're an expert at what you do.</i>

335
00:24:57,362 --> 00:24:59,353
<i>[ Dog Barking ]</i>

336
00:24:59,464 --> 00:25:01,591
<i>[ Floyd ]</i>
<i>I was a technician.</i>

337
00:25:03,168 --> 00:25:06,399
[ Speaking Vietnamese ]

338
00:25:06,505 --> 00:25:09,474
<i>[ Translator ] Everything just</i>
<i>collapsed under the bombs.</i>

339
00:25:09,574 --> 00:25:11,542
<i>Everything just caved in.</i>

340
00:25:17,048 --> 00:25:20,245
<i>It's like a bird and its nest.</i>

341
00:25:21,720 --> 00:25:24,587
<i>The way things are</i>
<i>with the house in the rubble,</i>

342
00:25:25,924 --> 00:25:29,758
<i>the bird comes home</i>
<i>and finds no nest.</i>

343
00:25:29,861 --> 00:25:33,888
<i>Where am I to find a place to sit</i>
<i>and work for something to eat?</i>

344
00:25:33,999 --> 00:25:37,730
<i>Even a bird needs a nest</i>
<i>it can go back to,</i>

345
00:25:37,836 --> 00:25:40,464
<i>crawl into for sleep and food.</i>

346
00:26:01,126 --> 00:26:03,026
[ Speaking Vietnamese ]

347
00:26:03,128 --> 00:26:05,790
<i>[ Translator ]</i>
<i>Look, they're focusing on us now.</i>

348
00:26:08,500 --> 00:26:13,130
<i>First they bomb as much as they please,</i>
<i>then they film.</i>

349
00:26:18,143 --> 00:26:20,941
<i>[ Man Speaking French ]</i>

350
00:26:22,881 --> 00:26:26,783
<i>[ Translator ] We fought</i>
<i>against the Chinese for 12 centuries.</i>

351
00:26:26,885 --> 00:26:29,513
<i>We fought against the French</i>
<i>for 100 years.</i>

352
00:26:33,925 --> 00:26:37,520
<i>And finally, when the war</i>
<i>was lost by the French in 1954...</i>

353
00:26:37,629 --> 00:26:39,961
<i>at the battle of Dien Bien Phu,</i>

354
00:26:40,065 --> 00:26:43,228
<i>the Vietnamese were liberated</i>
<i>from foreign oppression.</i>

355
00:26:48,440 --> 00:26:53,309
<i>But it was at that precise moment that</i>
<i>the Americans came to Vietnam.</i>

356
00:26:53,411 --> 00:26:57,780
<i>Little by little at first.</i>
<i>Then more and more as an invasion,</i>

357
00:26:57,882 --> 00:27:00,282
<i>an invasion of the American army.</i>

358
00:27:03,421 --> 00:27:06,356
<i>Five hundred thousand of them</i>
<i>in Vietnam.</i>

359
00:27:06,458 --> 00:27:10,258
<i>And this war</i>
<i>became a war of genocide.</i>

360
00:27:10,362 --> 00:27:13,627
<i>The people of North Vietnam</i>
<i>and South Vietnam...</i>

361
00:27:13,732 --> 00:27:18,795
<i>fight only for freedom,</i>
<i>independence and national unity.</i>

362
00:27:20,872 --> 00:27:26,003
This war is a war against
the American imperialists.

363
00:27:26,111 --> 00:27:29,444
This is our war for independence.

364
00:27:29,547 --> 00:27:32,107
-<i>[ Gunshot ]</i>
-<i>[''Yankee Doodle'']</i>

365
00:27:40,492 --> 00:27:44,724
What we are trying to put across this
afternoon is to get you to realize...

366
00:27:44,829 --> 00:27:47,662
that these weren't mythical,
hazy people from the past.

367
00:27:47,766 --> 00:27:49,996
These were very real people.

368
00:27:50,101 --> 00:27:53,935
When they rose up against
the most powerful army in the world,

369
00:27:54,039 --> 00:27:57,008
they were actually putting
everything on the line that they had:

370
00:27:57,108 --> 00:28:01,204
their homes, their wealth,
their past and their future.

371
00:28:01,312 --> 00:28:03,837
<i>[ Man On P.A.] ''We hold these truths</i>
<i>to be self-evident.</i>

372
00:28:03,948 --> 00:28:06,314
<i>That all men are created equal.</i>

373
00:28:06,418 --> 00:28:10,548
<i>That they are endowed by their creator</i>
<i>with certain unalienable rights.</i>

374
00:28:10,655 --> 00:28:16,093
<i>That among these are life, liberty</i>
<i>and the pursuit of happiness. ''</i>

375
00:28:16,194 --> 00:28:18,662
And when you judge the Revolution
and the problems and the success we had,

376
00:28:18,763 --> 00:28:20,663
it was a two-way street.

377
00:28:20,765 --> 00:28:23,893
A good many citizens
at the time of the Revolution...

378
00:28:24,002 --> 00:28:26,596
actually stayed
and fought with the British.

379
00:28:26,705 --> 00:28:28,730
It was close to being a civil war
in many areas.

380
00:28:28,840 --> 00:28:31,502
You actually split
many-many families.

381
00:28:31,609 --> 00:28:34,407
Thomas Jefferson said,
''The tree of revolution is--''

382
00:28:34,512 --> 00:28:36,412
or ''The tree of liberty is...

383
00:28:36,514 --> 00:28:39,950
watered by the blood of revolution
every generation.''

384
00:28:40,051 --> 00:28:44,454
And I think that's a little exaggerated,
but there's some truth to that.

385
00:28:44,556 --> 00:28:46,990
<i>[ Man On P.A.] The war had come</i>
<i>to Westchester County,</i>

386
00:28:47,092 --> 00:28:51,461
<i>but so too had independence</i>
<i>and a new responsibility.</i>

387
00:28:51,563 --> 00:28:54,623
Men are getting killed, men are killing.
That's the parallel.

388
00:28:54,733 --> 00:28:57,327
As far as politics, are you kidding?

389
00:28:57,435 --> 00:29:00,131
Oriental politics?
Don't put me on, man.

390
00:29:01,473 --> 00:29:02,963
<i>[ Man ]</i>
<i>Fire!</i>

391
00:29:04,876 --> 00:29:07,902
<i>[ Man ] We haven't found his weapon yet.</i>
<i>We're still looking for it.</i>

392
00:29:08,012 --> 00:29:09,912
-<i>[ Man #2 ] You got a weapon?</i>
- No, sir.

393
00:29:10,014 --> 00:29:11,914
<i>He had one, man.</i>
<i>This guy's got ammo.</i>

394
00:29:12,016 --> 00:29:14,746
<i>[ Man #3 ]</i>
<i>I'm planning to medivac this guy.</i>

395
00:29:14,853 --> 00:29:18,289
<i>[ Talking, Indistinct ]</i>

396
00:29:18,389 --> 00:29:20,323
[ Indistinct ]

397
00:29:20,425 --> 00:29:22,985
<i>[ Ellsberg ]</i>
<i>The people who are living in the jungle,</i>

398
00:29:23,094 --> 00:29:27,292
<i>under the bombs, without pay,</i>
<i>without their families,</i>

399
00:29:27,398 --> 00:29:30,663
<i>are doing so because</i>
<i>they are fighting for independence.</i>

400
00:29:30,769 --> 00:29:33,067
<i>Because they're fighting,</i>
<i>in this case, for unification...</i>

401
00:29:33,171 --> 00:29:35,264
<i>and they're fighting for revolution.</i>

402
00:29:35,373 --> 00:29:39,810
-<i>[ Man On Radio, Indistinct ]</i>
- [ Moaning ]

403
00:29:39,911 --> 00:29:42,311
[ Moaning Louder]

404
00:29:42,413 --> 00:29:47,441
Of course,
the name for a conflict...

405
00:29:47,552 --> 00:29:51,044
in which you're opposing a revolution
is counter-revolution.

406
00:29:51,156 --> 00:29:53,716
And this is something
We never admitted to ourselves at all.

407
00:29:53,825 --> 00:29:55,793
It's-It's what we were really doing.

408
00:29:55,894 --> 00:29:59,523
<i>[ Man ]</i>
<i>The letters and the reports we had...</i>

409
00:29:59,631 --> 00:30:03,123
<i>on Ho Chi Minh's attitude</i>
<i>back in 1 946</i>--

410
00:30:03,234 --> 00:30:07,603
<i>he wrote I think it was seven letters to</i>
<i>this government and received no reply.</i>

411
00:30:07,705 --> 00:30:12,802
The-The-The pathos, almost,
the sadness--

412
00:30:12,911 --> 00:30:16,312
Here's a man who felt
and believed the United States...

413
00:30:16,414 --> 00:30:19,747
would be sympathetic to his purpose
of gaining his independence...

414
00:30:19,851 --> 00:30:21,751
from a colonial power.

415
00:30:21,853 --> 00:30:25,016
And then to find we--
You know, this is what he'd read.

416
00:30:25,123 --> 00:30:28,581
He'd been here, read our Constitution
and Declaration of Independence.

417
00:30:28,693 --> 00:30:31,719
He thought surely the United States
would be interested.

418
00:30:31,830 --> 00:30:34,355
We had testimony in the committee
that his one worry...

419
00:30:34,465 --> 00:30:36,365
was that
it was so insignificant--

420
00:30:36,467 --> 00:30:40,631
Vietnam was so far away, insignificant--
we would never bother about it.

421
00:30:40,738 --> 00:30:45,641
It's too small to ever attract
the attention of the United States.

422
00:30:45,743 --> 00:30:47,643
<i>He was sure in his own mind...</i>

423
00:30:47,745 --> 00:30:50,578
<i>that if we ever put our minds</i>
<i>in focus upon it, we would be for him.</i>

424
00:30:50,682 --> 00:30:55,142
<i>How different history would have</i>
<i>been for us and for them...</i>

425
00:30:55,253 --> 00:30:58,154
<i>if we had felt a common interest...</i>

426
00:30:58,256 --> 00:31:01,419
<i>in the colonial province like Vietnam...</i>

427
00:31:01,526 --> 00:31:03,494
<i>seeking its independence</i>
<i>from France.</i>

428
00:31:04,696 --> 00:31:06,596
The Ho Chi Minh of'56,

429
00:31:06,698 --> 00:31:09,895
I don't think could have got elected
dogcatcher in South Vietnam.

430
00:31:10,001 --> 00:31:14,700
Ho Chi Minh, uh, dead--
[ Laughing ]

431
00:31:14,806 --> 00:31:18,003
could beat any candidate
we've ever put up in Vietnam.

432
00:31:20,812 --> 00:31:24,612
<i>[ Man ]</i>
<i>You asked me about my oldest son Bing.</i>

433
