01:00:04,167 --> 01:00:10,072
<i>And for those</i>
<i>who only wanted to be free</i>

849
01:00:12,075 --> 01:00:15,806
<i>Only Uncle Sam's great heroes</i>

850
01:00:15,912 --> 01:00:18,403
<i>Get to go there</i>

851
01:00:19,983 --> 01:00:23,384
- Stand up.
-<i>Now don't say that it's not right</i>

852
01:00:23,486 --> 01:00:27,718
<i>For there to be</i>

853
01:00:27,824 --> 01:00:32,022
<i>[ Man ] Keep it flat.</i>
<i>Just like you do with your good leg.</i>

854
01:00:32,128 --> 01:00:34,562
<i>Now try to walk.</i>

855
01:00:34,664 --> 01:00:37,064
<i>'Cause it's waving there</i>

856
01:00:37,166 --> 01:00:40,795
-<i>For you and for me</i>
- <i>Not high enough?</i>

857
01:00:42,505 --> 01:00:45,565
<i>Well, it really isn't that much.</i>
<i>We were just walking and</i>--

858
01:00:45,675 --> 01:00:50,578
We were walking on a patrol
and, uh, we ran into an ambush.

859
01:00:50,680 --> 01:00:52,580
About six, seven guys
really got hurt.

860
01:00:52,682 --> 01:00:56,083
Ran into a battalion ambush,
they said it was.

861
01:00:56,185 --> 01:01:00,588
And it was supposed to be one
of the biggest ambushes of Tet season.

862
01:01:00,690 --> 01:01:06,595
And we called in two or three medivacs,
and they got hit.

863
01:01:06,696 --> 01:01:10,598
So, finally, the last one
came in and got us out.

864
01:01:10,700 --> 01:01:14,761
From that, I never saw any of the others
I was with, except for one or two.

865
01:01:14,871 --> 01:01:16,771
And that was about it.

866
01:01:16,873 --> 01:01:20,468
Most of the guys I keep in touch with
are guys in the hospital.

867
01:01:20,576 --> 01:01:22,771
They usually have a reunion
once a year.

868
01:01:22,879 --> 01:01:24,847
<i>[ Hammering ]</i>

869
01:01:26,382 --> 01:01:29,180
That's about it. There's really
not that much to talk about.

870
01:01:32,321 --> 01:01:37,884
Here we are for one thing that we said,
and I don't give a shit now.

871
01:01:37,994 --> 01:01:40,360
I don't care
about the football game now.

872
01:01:40,463 --> 01:01:42,624
I don't care about anything now.

873
01:01:42,732 --> 01:01:46,634
The one thing that we wanna show
these bastards with Masillon pride...

874
01:01:46,736 --> 01:01:49,136
is that we come down
and show 'em a great Masillon effort.

875
01:01:49,238 --> 01:01:52,298
And what the piss you doing?
What are ya doing?

876
01:01:52,408 --> 01:01:54,308
Get going!
Goddamn it, Tony!

877
01:01:54,410 --> 01:01:56,640
Don't let 'em beat us!
Don't let 'em beat us!

878
01:01:56,746 --> 01:01:58,646
Let's go!
Show 'em Masillon pride.

879
01:01:58,748 --> 01:02:01,148
Come on! Go!
- [ Players ] Go!

880
01:02:01,250 --> 01:02:03,616
- Go, go, go, go!
-<i>[ Shouting Continues ]</i>

881
01:02:03,720 --> 01:02:06,712
<i>[ Crowd Cheering ]</i>

882
01:02:18,301 --> 01:02:20,394
<i>[ Man ]</i>
<i>Get him! Get him!</i>

883
01:02:21,771 --> 01:02:24,171
Defense, defense

884
01:02:24,273 --> 01:02:28,107
Defense, defense, defense

885
01:02:28,211 --> 01:02:30,406
Make no mistake about it.

886
01:02:32,048 --> 01:02:34,175
I don't want a man in here...
[ Pounding Emphatically ]

887
01:02:34,283 --> 01:02:37,684
to go back home
thinking otherwise.

888
01:02:37,787 --> 01:02:40,085
We are going to win.

889
01:02:49,832 --> 01:02:52,357
<i>[ Commotion, Baby Crying ]</i>

890
01:03:01,444 --> 01:03:03,275
Go, motherfucker! Go!

891
01:03:03,379 --> 01:03:05,279
<i>[ Newscaster ]</i>
<i>Since the Lunar New Year,</i>

892
01:03:05,381 --> 01:03:08,214
<i>the Vietcong and North Vietnamese</i>
<i>have proved they are capable...</i>

893
01:03:08,317 --> 01:03:10,808
<i>of bold and impressive</i>
<i>military moves...</i>

894
01:03:10,920 --> 01:03:13,718
<i>that Americans here</i>
<i>never dreamed could be achieved.</i>

895
01:03:13,823 --> 01:03:18,317
<i>Whether the Vietcong can sustain</i>
<i>this onslaught long remains to be seen,</i>

896
01:03:18,427 --> 01:03:20,657
<i>but whatever turn this war now takes,</i>

897
01:03:20,763 --> 01:03:23,891
<i>the capture of the U.S. Embassy</i>
<i>in Saigon for seven hours...</i>

898
01:03:24,000 --> 01:03:27,401
<i>will be a story to rally</i>
<i>and inspire the Vietcong.</i>

899
01:03:27,503 --> 01:03:32,099
<i>Don North, ABC news,</i>
<i>at the U.S. Embassy in Saigon.</i>

900
01:03:32,208 --> 01:03:36,406
<i>I know that, as was the case in</i>
<i>the Battle of the Bulge in World War II,</i>

901
01:03:36,512 --> 01:03:39,413
that after the enemy exposed himself,
we would defeat him.

902
01:03:39,515 --> 01:03:43,349
He would be weakened,
and we could follow that up.

903
01:03:43,452 --> 01:03:45,750
Through the use of, uh,

904
01:03:45,855 --> 01:03:49,916
the maximum military force
that we could bring to bear on him,

905
01:03:50,026 --> 01:03:52,927
through the bombing,
through the mining of the harbors,

906
01:03:53,029 --> 01:03:55,429
through the cutting
of his lines of communication,

907
01:03:55,531 --> 01:03:57,761
by moving in
and cleaning out his sanctuaries,

908
01:03:57,867 --> 01:04:00,165
the enemy would have no choice...

909
01:04:00,269 --> 01:04:02,294
but to come
to some accommodation.

910
01:04:02,405 --> 01:04:04,873
<i>[ Man ]</i>
<i>In the beginning of 1968,</i>

911
01:04:04,974 --> 01:04:08,933
<i>General Westmoreland</i>
<i>needed 206,000 more troops.</i>

912
01:04:09,045 --> 01:04:12,014
<i>We met hour after hour</i>
<i>after hour in the Pentagon.</i>

913
01:04:12,114 --> 01:04:17,746
And I started in and asked
the Joint Chiefs of Staff,

914
01:04:17,854 --> 01:04:20,482
<i>''How long do you think that</i>
<i>we'll still be in the war?''</i>

915
01:04:20,590 --> 01:04:22,717
None of them knew.

916
01:04:22,825 --> 01:04:27,194
''Uh, do you think that
the 206,000 men will be enough?''

917
01:04:27,296 --> 01:04:29,196
Nobody knew.

918
01:04:29,298 --> 01:04:33,291
''Uh, might we have to send more men?''
''Well, possibly.''

919
01:04:33,402 --> 01:04:35,302
''Well, in six months?''
''We don't know.''

920
01:04:35,404 --> 01:04:37,065
''Ayear? Eighteen months?''

921
01:04:37,173 --> 01:04:39,733
I couldn't get answers
to these questions.

922
01:04:39,842 --> 01:04:43,801
By the end of that
four-day interrogation,

923
01:04:43,913 --> 01:04:47,747
I was getting down--by the end of it--
into very serious questions,

924
01:04:47,850 --> 01:04:53,152
''Do any of you men,
as you look at it objectively,

925
01:04:53,256 --> 01:04:58,660
do you find any diminution
in the will of the enemy to fight?''

926
01:04:58,761 --> 01:05:00,991
Well, they said,
''No, we guess we don't.''

927
01:05:01,097 --> 01:05:04,498
''Are they sending the same number of men
down through the Ho Chi Minh trail?''

928
01:05:04,600 --> 01:05:08,502
''Well, yes, and even
they might be a little more.''

929
01:05:08,604 --> 01:05:13,507
''And how about our bombing? We've placed
great reliance on our bombing.

930
01:05:13,609 --> 01:05:15,907
Is our bombing stopping them?''
''No.''

931
01:05:16,012 --> 01:05:19,448
''Well, what is the amount of attrition
that our bombing's causing?''

932
01:05:19,548 --> 01:05:22,779
''Well, maybe 10 to 15 percent.''

933
01:05:22,885 --> 01:05:25,183
So I remember
asking one question.

934
01:05:25,288 --> 01:05:30,590
''If a North Vietnamese field commander
in South Vietnam needed 1,000 men--''

935
01:05:30,693 --> 01:05:32,593
They said, ''Yes.''

936
01:05:32,695 --> 01:05:36,324
''If he asked for, say, 1,200 men,

937
01:05:36,432 --> 01:05:38,332
1,000 would get through?''

938
01:05:38,434 --> 01:05:40,334
''Well, that's right.''

939
01:05:40,436 --> 01:05:43,872
''Then he'd have the thousand he needed.''
''Well, yes. That's so.''

940
01:05:43,973 --> 01:05:46,874
Well, this type of interrogation--

941
01:05:46,976 --> 01:05:49,206
Finally, by the end
of four or five days,

942
01:05:49,312 --> 01:05:52,042
I must say that my thinking...

943
01:05:52,148 --> 01:05:56,244
had undergone
a very substantial revolution.

944
01:05:56,352 --> 01:06:00,812
All we are saying

945
01:06:00,923 --> 01:06:05,826
Is give peace a chance

946
01:06:05,928 --> 01:06:10,228
All we are saying

947
01:06:10,333 --> 01:06:13,131
Is give peace a chance

948
01:06:13,235 --> 01:06:16,466
<i>[ Man ]</i>
<i>Come on, everybody!</i>

949
01:06:16,572 --> 01:06:20,838
All we are saying

950
01:06:20,943 --> 01:06:25,710
Is give peace a chance

951
01:06:25,815 --> 01:06:28,579
Power to the people
Stop the war

952
01:06:28,684 --> 01:06:31,619
Power to the people
Stop the war

953
01:06:31,721 --> 01:06:35,248
<i>[ Man ] As long as</i>
<i>the American President...</i>

954
01:06:35,358 --> 01:06:38,794
<i>is commander in chief...</i>

955
01:06:38,894 --> 01:06:44,594
<i>of the biggest war machine</i>
<i>in human history,</i>

956
01:06:44,700 --> 01:06:47,760
<i>with bases on every continent,</i>

957
01:06:47,870 --> 01:06:50,600
<i>we are going to get into trouble.</i>

958
01:06:50,706 --> 01:06:56,076
<i>Our enemy is the growing militarization</i>
<i>of American life.</i>

959
01:06:56,178 --> 01:07:00,046
<i>Our enemy</i>
<i>is American imperialism.</i>

960
01:07:00,149 --> 01:07:02,447
<i>And there is an awakening.</i>

961
01:07:03,986 --> 01:07:07,945
The enemy was on the ropes
after the Tet offensive was over.

962
01:07:08,057 --> 01:07:10,548
And it's like two boxers
in the ring.

963
01:07:10,659 --> 01:07:12,786
One boxer has the other one
on the ropes,

964
01:07:12,895 --> 01:07:15,796
but the man
who is about to be the victor...

965
01:07:15,898 --> 01:07:18,366
has his second
throw the towel in.

966
01:07:18,467 --> 01:07:20,526
Accordingly,

967
01:07:22,004 --> 01:07:24,029
I shall not seek...

968
01:07:25,241 --> 01:07:27,971
and I will not accept...

969
01:07:28,077 --> 01:07:31,877
the nomination of my party
for another term as your president.

970
01:07:32,948 --> 01:07:34,848
I don't think we helped 'em one bit.

971
01:07:34,950 --> 01:07:37,646
All I think we've done is
destroyed their country, laid it waste.

972
01:07:37,753 --> 01:07:40,415
No. I don't think we helped 'em.

973
01:07:40,523 --> 01:07:44,084
As fellow human beings, I don't think
they should be there doing that.

974
01:07:44,193 --> 01:07:46,684
Certainly a mature person
can say they made a mistake.

975
01:07:46,796 --> 01:07:48,263
Why can't a government?

976
01:07:48,364 --> 01:07:52,767
You let us all go off to war and said,
''Yea, team. Fight in Vietnam,''

977
01:07:52,868 --> 01:07:55,666
and all this kinda shit
in 1 965 through 1 968.

978
01:07:55,771 --> 01:08:00,174
Now 1 968 comes along and ''Boo, team.
Come on home,'' and all this shit.

979
01:08:00,276 --> 01:08:03,006
''And don't say nothin' about it,
'cause we don't want to hear about it...

980
01:08:03,112 --> 01:08:05,012
'cause it's upsetting
around dinnertime.''

981
01:08:05,114 --> 01:08:07,344
Well, Goddamn. It upset me
for a whole goddamn year.

982
01:08:07,450 --> 01:08:10,351
It upset a lot of people to the point
where they're fuckin' dead, you know?

983
01:08:10,453 --> 01:08:13,354
All this shit. You don't wanna
hear about it? I'll tell you every day.

984
01:08:13,456 --> 01:08:15,856
Make you sit out
and puke on your dinner, you dig?

985
01:08:15,958 --> 01:08:18,859
Because you got me over there,
and now you done brought me back here...

986
01:08:18,961 --> 01:08:22,021
and you wanna forget it so somebody else
can go do it somewhere else.

987
01:08:22,131 --> 01:08:24,190
Hell no. Uh-uh.
You gonna hear it all.

988
01:08:24,300 --> 01:08:28,532
Every day as long as you live, because
it's gonna be with me as long as I live.

989
01:08:28,637 --> 01:08:30,730
When I get up in the morning,
when John gets up,

990
01:08:30,840 --> 01:08:32,865
when a lot of dudes sitting here get up,

991
01:08:32,975 --> 01:08:35,034
man, their gut hurts
because they got shot there.

992
01:08:35,144 --> 01:08:38,045
I gotta put on an arm and a leg,
'cause it ain't there no more, you dig?

993
01:08:38,147 --> 01:08:41,548
Now, my man's got a hole in his stomach.
He can't work right, you know?

994
01:08:41,650 --> 01:08:45,051
You do something about that.
Make that all disappear, you dig?

995
01:08:45,154 --> 01:08:47,054
Make it all go away with the 6:00 news.

996
01:08:47,156 --> 01:08:49,716
Turn it off or switch it
to another channel.

997
01:08:49,825 --> 01:08:53,056
Uh-Uh. To hell with that, you dig?
It's here and it's for real.

998
01:08:53,162 --> 01:08:56,063
And it's gonna happen again
unless these folks get off their ass...

999
01:08:56,165 --> 01:08:58,156
and realize it <i>has</i> happened.

1000
01:08:58,267 --> 01:09:01,100
<i>Power to the people</i>

1001
01:09:01,203 --> 01:09:04,229
<i>Power to the people</i>

1002
01:09:04,340 --> 01:09:08,743
<i>The country is ready to pass</i>
<i>a reasoned judgment on this war.</i>

1003
01:09:08,844 --> 01:09:12,575
The people have judged, I think,
that it's unwise and immoral...

1004
01:09:12,681 --> 01:09:15,411
and not in the national interest
of this country...

1005
01:09:15,518 --> 01:09:17,986
and that, therefore,
it must be brought to an end.

1006
01:09:18,087 --> 01:09:20,555
<i>[ Cheering, Applause ]</i>

1007
01:09:22,224 --> 01:09:25,751
For 20 years, first the French,
and then the United States...

1008
01:09:25,861 --> 01:09:29,092
had been predicting victory in Vietnam.

1009
01:09:29,198 --> 01:09:32,258
In 1961 and in 1962,

1010
01:09:32,368 --> 01:09:35,769
as well as 1966 and 1967,

1011
01:09:35,871 --> 01:09:38,271
we have been told
that the tide is turning,

1012
01:09:38,374 --> 01:09:40,433
there is a light
at the end of the tunnel,

1013
01:09:40,543 --> 01:09:43,444
we can soon bring our troops home,

1014
01:09:43,546 --> 01:09:46,515
victory is near, the enemy is tiring.

1015
01:09:46,615 --> 01:09:48,640
Once, in 1962,

1016
01:09:48,751 --> 01:09:53,279
I participated
in such a prediction myself.

1017
01:09:53,389 --> 01:09:56,449
But for 20 years,
we have been wrong.

1018
01:09:56,559 --> 01:09:58,959
The history of conflict
among nations...

1019
01:09:59,061 --> 01:10:04,124
does not record another such lengthy
and consistent chronicle of error...

1020
01:10:04,233 --> 01:10:06,701
as we have shown in Vietnam.

1021
01:10:06,802 --> 01:10:09,737
I had just given the policy line,

1022
01:10:09,838 --> 01:10:13,296
stayed up all night with
Adam Walinsky and Peter Edelman,

1023
01:10:13,409 --> 01:10:15,309
helping on a speech
for Robert Kennedy...

1024
01:10:15,411 --> 01:10:19,040
which proved to be his last speech
given in San Francisco here...

1025
01:10:19,148 --> 01:10:22,311
to a businessman's luncheon on Vietnam.

1026
01:10:22,418 --> 01:10:26,718
Uh, I went up with some corrections
last thing in the morning...

1027
01:10:26,822 --> 01:10:30,155
and shook hands with him
in his bathrobe as he stood there.

1028
01:10:30,259 --> 01:10:33,820
And then he came down from
the Ambassador Hotel and got into a car.

1029
01:10:33,929 --> 01:10:38,161
We were struck with how easy
it was to get onto that floor...

1030
01:10:38,267 --> 01:10:40,167
and approach him at that point.

1031
01:10:40,269 --> 01:10:42,237
At the conference
on lessons on Vietnam,

1032
01:10:42,338 --> 01:10:45,569
of course, in the morning I learned
that Robert Kennedy had died.

1033
01:10:52,114 --> 01:10:54,241
Well--
[ Sighs ]

1034
01:10:56,585 --> 01:10:58,951
So--
[ Clears Throat ]

1035
01:10:59,054 --> 01:11:01,750
So, uh--
[ Exhales Deeply ]

1036
01:11:06,128 --> 01:11:10,258
Well, that was a way
for a lot of people to feel powerless.

1037
01:11:15,137 --> 01:11:17,264
[ Sighs ]

1038
01:11:20,776 --> 01:11:23,210
So, um,

1039
01:11:23,312 --> 01:11:26,770
it began to look as if there was no way
to change this country.

1040
01:11:27,950 --> 01:11:30,111
<i>[ Machine Gun Fire ]</i>

1041
01:11:31,153 --> 01:11:34,020
<i>[ Conversation, Indistinct ]</i>

1042
01:11:58,747 --> 01:12:01,944
<i>[ Machine Gun Fire Continues ]</i>

1043
01:12:19,968 --> 01:12:22,869
<i>[ Clifford ] We'd been going</i>
<i>down this road for so many years,</i>

1044
01:12:22,971 --> 01:12:27,101
<i>and I had felt so strongly before</i>
<i>that this was the right policy,</i>

1045
01:12:27,209 --> 01:12:29,769
<i>that it was difficult</i>
<i>for me to change.</i>

1046
01:12:29,878 --> 01:12:35,248
<i>I know now that the domino theory</i>
<i>was a false theory.</i>

1047
01:12:35,351 --> 01:12:39,981
<i>I know now that we should not</i>
<i>have become involved.</i>

1048
01:12:40,089 --> 01:12:42,557
As far as I'm concerned today,

1049
01:12:42,658 --> 01:12:44,956
I have no hesitancy
whatsoever...

1050
01:12:45,060 --> 01:12:48,791
in saying I could not
have been more wrong...

1051
01:12:48,897 --> 01:12:51,195
in my attitude toward Vietnam.

1052
01:12:56,305 --> 01:12:57,932
...ground combat,

1053
01:12:58,040 --> 01:13:00,565
Vietnamese cross of gallantry
with a silver star,

1054
01:13:00,676 --> 01:13:02,644
gallantry in ground combat,

1055
01:13:02,745 --> 01:13:05,976
four air medals,
an ''I was there'' ribbon.

1056
01:13:06,081 --> 01:13:09,050
<i>[ Cheering, Applause ]</i>

1057
01:13:11,553 --> 01:13:14,488
I got a colonel that's flying upstairs,
and he's gettin' down on me...

1058
01:13:14,590 --> 01:13:18,321
and he's saying, ''Take the hill,
take the hill, take the hill.''

1059
01:13:18,427 --> 01:13:21,487
So I got together
with the tank commander...

1060
01:13:21,597 --> 01:13:23,827
and I said,
''Look, let's take three tanks...

1061
01:13:23,932 --> 01:13:26,833
and we'll walk the A.R.V.N.
up the hill, you know?

1062
01:13:26,935 --> 01:13:30,098
And we'll lay down a base of fire
as we're going.''

1063
01:13:30,205 --> 01:13:33,504
He says, ''Okay.'' I got with the A.R.V.N.
and says, ''Let's fly.''

1064
01:13:33,609 --> 01:13:36,510
So I popped up
behind the lead tank...

1065
01:13:36,612 --> 01:13:39,137
and, uh, started to go up the hill.

1066
01:13:39,248 --> 01:13:43,617
And everything was cool,
until we started taking fire.

1067
01:13:43,719 --> 01:13:46,916
And, uh, the A.R.V.N. started to split.

1068
01:13:49,124 --> 01:13:51,285
And that's when I got it.

1069
01:13:51,393 --> 01:13:56,296
I said, ''Oh, my God. I'm hit.''
I couldn't believe it, you know?

1070
01:13:56,398 --> 01:13:58,525
''I can't believe it. I'm really hit.''

1071
01:13:58,634 --> 01:14:01,194
And my first, first thought...

1072
01:14:01,303 --> 01:14:03,931
was Kay, my girl, you know?

1073
01:14:05,140 --> 01:14:07,370
[ Chuckles ]
It's gonna sound stupid,

1074
01:14:07,476 --> 01:14:10,138
but I'm--but my thought was
''She'll kill me.''

1075
01:14:10,245 --> 01:14:13,908
You know, here I was dying and I was
worried that she was gonna kill me.

1076
01:14:14,016 --> 01:14:18,976
<i>But then I realized that I didn't</i>
<i>have to worry because I was dying.</i>

1077
01:14:19,087 --> 01:14:22,716
<i>It's all over.</i>
<i>And for what,you know?</i>

1078
01:14:22,825 --> 01:14:25,623
<i>My last</i>--
<i>My last conscious thought...</i>

1079
01:14:25,727 --> 01:14:29,128
<i>was ''I can't believe it.</i>
<i>I'm dying.</i>

1080
01:14:29,231 --> 01:14:32,564
On this shitty piece of ground,
I'm dying...

1081
01:14:32,668 --> 01:14:34,659
and I can't fuckin' believe it.''

1082
01:14:34,770 --> 01:14:36,931
Bobby was a surfer,
he was a wrestler,

1083
01:14:37,039 --> 01:14:38,939
he was a long-distance runner.

1084
01:14:39,041 --> 01:14:41,805
We danced. He was active.
Active, active.

1085
01:14:41,910 --> 01:14:44,105
<i>Our whole life was active.</i>

1086
01:14:44,213 --> 01:14:46,374
<i>And now they're telling me</i>
<i>that he's paralyzed.</i>

1087
01:14:46,482 --> 01:14:49,417
<i>He couldn't believe it</i>
<i>and I couldn't believe it. Right now...</i>

1088
01:14:49,518 --> 01:14:53,420
<i>Bobby's not a boyfriend.</i>
<i>He's not a husband. He's not a brother.</i>

1089
01:14:53,522 --> 01:14:56,514
<i>It-It's very</i>--

1090
01:14:56,625 --> 01:14:58,525
<i>[ Sighs ]</i>

1091
01:14:58,627 --> 01:15:00,595
<i>It's very hard.</i>

1092
01:15:00,696 --> 01:15:02,926
<i>[ Muller ]</i>
<i>What hurts the most</i>--

1093
01:15:03,031 --> 01:15:05,226
<i>and this is a purely personal thing,</i>
<i>you know?</i>

1094
01:15:05,334 --> 01:15:08,997
Right, wrong or indifferent,
that's how I feel.

1095
01:15:09,104 --> 01:15:11,095
When I was in the Marine Corps,

1096
01:15:11,206 --> 01:15:14,107
I remember I was in the Marine Corps
barracks in Washington--

1097
01:15:14,209 --> 01:15:16,177
They call it
''A,'' ''F,'' and ''I.''

1098
01:15:16,278 --> 01:15:19,111
And they had
the Marine Corps drill team there.

1099
01:15:19,214 --> 01:15:23,275
And I was standing at attention
in my uniform...

1100
01:15:23,385 --> 01:15:25,285
and they were playing
the ''Marine Corps Hymn''.

1101
01:15:25,387 --> 01:15:28,618
And then they played
the ''Star-Spangled Banner.''

1102
01:15:28,724 --> 01:15:30,919
And I actually started to cry.

1103
01:15:32,394 --> 01:15:37,058
I cried because I was so proud
to be an American, you know?

1104
01:15:37,165 --> 01:15:39,963
And I was so proud
to be a marine...

1105
01:15:40,068 --> 01:15:43,037
and in uniform,
standing there at attention.

1106
01:15:45,073 --> 01:15:48,873
That-That represented
so much to me...

1107
01:15:48,977 --> 01:15:52,469
in the way of life and--

1108
01:15:52,581 --> 01:15:55,072
That's gone, you know?

1109
01:15:55,183 --> 01:15:58,482
And that hurt.
That <i>hurts.</i>

1110
01:15:58,587 --> 01:16:00,555
That's what I'm bitter about.

1111
01:16:03,592 --> 01:16:07,153
<i>Johnny, get your gun</i>
<i>get your gun, get your gun</i>

1112
01:16:07,262 --> 01:16:10,754
<i>Take it on the run</i>
<i>on the run, on the run</i>

1113
01:16:10,866 --> 01:16:14,427
<i>Hear them calling you and me</i>

1114
01:16:14,536 --> 01:16:18,472
<i>Every son of liberty</i>

1115
01:16:18,574 --> 01:16:21,771
<i>Over there, over there</i>

1116
01:16:21,877 --> 01:16:25,813
<i>Send the word</i>
<i>Send the word over there</i>

1117
01:16:25,914 --> 01:16:29,350
<i>That the yanks are coming</i>
<i>the yanks are coming</i>

1118
01:16:29,451 --> 01:16:32,352
<i>The drums rum-tumming everywhere</i>

1119
01:16:32,454 --> 01:16:36,618
<i>So prepare, say a prayer</i>

1120
01:16:36,725 --> 01:16:39,523
<i>Send the word</i>
<i>Send the word to beware</i>

1121
01:16:39,628 --> 01:16:43,223
<i>We'll be over</i>
<i>We're coming over</i>

1122
01:16:43,332 --> 01:16:47,598
<i>And we won't come back</i>
<i>till it's over over there</i>

1123
01:16:49,071 --> 01:16:51,801
<i>[ Machine Gun Fire ]</i>

1124
01:16:54,443 --> 01:16:58,539
Ha! Didn't think we were here,
did you, you dirty rotten rats!

1125
01:16:58,647 --> 01:17:00,740
We're still here!
We'll always be here!

1126
01:17:00,849 --> 01:17:04,216
<i>So prepare, say a prayer</i>

1127
01:17:04,319 --> 01:17:07,413
<i>Send the word</i>
<i>Send the word to beware</i>

1128
01:17:07,522 --> 01:17:11,390
<i>We'll be over</i>
<i>We're coming over</i>

1129
01:17:11,493 --> 01:17:15,623
<i>And we won't come back</i>
<i>till it's over over there</i>

1130
01:17:21,303 --> 01:17:25,137
Truman lied from 1 950 on...

1131
01:17:25,240 --> 01:17:28,141
on the nature and purposes
of the French involvement,

1132
01:17:28,243 --> 01:17:30,734
the colonial reconquest of Vietnam...

1133
01:17:30,846 --> 01:17:34,077
that we were financing
and encouraging.

1134
01:17:34,182 --> 01:17:36,582
Eisenhower lied
about the reasons for...

1135
01:17:36,685 --> 01:17:39,085
and the nature
of our involvement with Diem,

1136
01:17:39,187 --> 01:17:41,849
and the fact that he was in power,
essentially,

1137
01:17:41,957 --> 01:17:46,257
because of American support,
American money, and for no other reason.

1138
01:17:46,361 --> 01:17:51,663
Kennedy lied about the type
of involvement we were doing there,

1139
01:17:51,767 --> 01:17:53,667
our own combat involvement,

1140
01:17:53,769 --> 01:17:57,261
and about the recommendations that were
made to him for greater involvement.

1141
01:17:57,372 --> 01:17:59,272
President Kennedy lied about...

1142
01:17:59,374 --> 01:18:02,468
the degree of our participation
in the overthrow of Diem.

1143
01:18:03,879 --> 01:18:08,111
The, um,--Johnson, of course,
lied and lied and lied...

1144
01:18:08,216 --> 01:18:10,741
about our provocations
against the North Vietnamese...

1145
01:18:10,852 --> 01:18:13,616
prior to and after
the Tonkin Gulf incidents,

1146
01:18:13,722 --> 01:18:17,283
about the plans
for bombing North Vietnam,

1147
01:18:17,392 --> 01:18:21,624
and the nature of the buildup...

1148
01:18:21,730 --> 01:18:24,130
of American troops in Vietnam.

1149
01:18:24,232 --> 01:18:26,200
Nixon, as we now know,

1150
01:18:26,301 --> 01:18:28,633
misled and lied
to the American public...

1151
01:18:28,737 --> 01:18:32,173
for the first months of his office
in terms of our bombing of Cambodia...

1152
01:18:32,274 --> 01:18:34,674
and of Laos,
ground operations in Laos,

1153
01:18:36,011 --> 01:18:39,469
the reasons for our invasion
of Cambodia and of Laos,

1154
01:18:39,581 --> 01:18:43,984
and the prospects for the mining
at Haiphong that came about in 1 972,

1155
01:18:44,086 --> 01:18:46,680
but was envisioned
as early as 1969.

1156
01:18:47,989 --> 01:18:51,584
The American public
was lied to month by month...

1157
01:18:51,693 --> 01:18:54,594
by each of these
five administrations.

1158
01:18:54,696 --> 01:18:58,325
As I say, it's a tribute
to the American public,

1159
01:18:58,433 --> 01:19:02,836
that their leaders perceived
that they had to be lied to.

1160
01:19:02,938 --> 01:19:07,272
It's no tribute to us
that it was so easy to fool the public.

1161
01:19:07,375 --> 01:19:09,843
We have adopted a plan...

1162
01:19:09,945 --> 01:19:13,403
which we have worked out in cooperation
with the South Vietnamese...

1163
01:19:13,515 --> 01:19:18,350
for the complete withdrawal
of all U.S. combat ground forces...

1164
01:19:18,453 --> 01:19:21,854
and their replacement
by South Vietnamese forces...

1165
01:19:21,957 --> 01:19:24,858
on an orderly,
scheduled timetable.

1166
01:19:24,960 --> 01:19:28,691
This withdrawal will be made
from strength and not from weakness.

1167
01:19:28,797 --> 01:19:31,357
As South Vietnamese forces
become stronger,

1168
01:19:31,466 --> 01:19:35,459
the rate of American withdrawal
can become greater.

1169
01:19:35,570 --> 01:19:38,038
<i>[ Man On P.A. Speaking Vietnamese ]</i>

1170
01:19:38,140 --> 01:19:41,974
<i>[ Translator ]</i>
<i>Congratulations to Battalion 33 2...</i>

1171
01:19:42,077 --> 01:19:45,706
<i>on your recent victories</i>
<i>over the communists.</i>

1172
01:19:45,814 --> 01:19:49,716
<i>We ask ourselves,</i>
<i>''When will peace come?''</i>

1173
01:19:49,818 --> 01:19:53,379
<i>And I tell you, if you chase</i>
<i>the communists back to the north,</i>

1174
01:19:53,488 --> 01:19:56,457
<i>there won't be any war</i>
<i>in this hamlet.</i>

1175
01:19:56,558 --> 01:19:59,891
<i>Help rebuild the houses.</i>

1176
01:19:59,995 --> 01:20:02,122
<i>Help the people.</i>

1177
01:20:03,832 --> 01:20:06,562
<i>Rid the hamlet of all V.C...</i>

1178
01:20:06,668 --> 01:20:09,296
<i>so there will be no more suffering</i>
<i>and destruction...</i>

1179
01:20:09,404 --> 01:20:12,862
<i>for ourselves</i>
<i>and our compatriots.</i>

1180
01:20:14,242 --> 01:20:17,405
- [ Speaking Vietnamese ]
- [ American Shouts ]

1181
01:20:17,512 --> 01:20:20,242
Oh, my friend.
[ Laughing ]

1182
01:20:20,348 --> 01:20:22,407
- How you doing? Good to see you again.
- You just get back?

1183
01:20:22,517 --> 01:20:25,577
- Yeah. How you doing, men?
- Very good to see you.

1184
01:20:25,687 --> 01:20:27,917
How you doing?
Trung, good seeing you.

1185
01:20:28,023 --> 01:20:31,424
- <i>Good to see you, sir.</i>
- How you doing? Fine.

1186
01:20:31,526 --> 01:20:34,427
Just came in this afternoon, sir.
Been very quiet?

1187
01:20:34,529 --> 01:20:37,930
- Except last time, when the, uh--
- When the rockets went off?

1188
01:20:38,033 --> 01:20:39,933
- [ Laughs ]
- Yeah.

1189
01:20:40,035 --> 01:20:43,027
Very nice.
I read about it in <i>Stars And Stripes.</i>

1190
01:20:43,138 --> 01:20:45,606
That's one of our success stories here,
this battalion is.

1191
01:20:45,707 --> 01:20:47,766
We had a real, uh--
a lot of trouble with it.

1192
01:20:47,876 --> 01:20:50,276
We just gave, uh,
four bronze stars...

1193
01:20:50,378 --> 01:20:53,438
and five Ar-Comms
with V-device this week...

1194
01:20:53,548 --> 01:20:57,279
to a battalion commander and
three of his officers and five soldiers.

1195
01:20:57,385 --> 01:21:00,786
And we have six N-pac awards...

1196
01:21:00,889 --> 01:21:03,449
pending for
last Saturday night's action...

1197
01:21:03,558 --> 01:21:06,356
where we killed six V.C.
and captured nine weapons.

1198
01:21:06,461 --> 01:21:07,428
Good grief.

1199
01:21:07,529 --> 01:21:12,796
<i>He had been the recon</i>
<i>company commander of the, uh, 263rd...</i>

1200
01:21:12,901 --> 01:21:17,634
<i>and he'd done a real tremendous job</i>
<i>just as recon company commander.</i>

1201
01:21:17,739 --> 01:21:20,799
And then they moved him over here.

1202
01:21:20,909 --> 01:21:23,469
In a ten-day period or two-week period,
he completely reversed it.

1203
01:21:23,578 --> 01:21:28,538
They had the battalion here
under a very poor major.

1204
01:21:28,650 --> 01:21:32,142
They had it to the point
where the company commanders...

1205
01:21:32,254 --> 01:21:35,485
were throwing down their weapons
and crying--or at least one of them did.

1206
01:21:35,590 --> 01:21:38,491
Ten days later they had
a big contact with the V.C...

1207
01:21:38,593 --> 01:21:43,690
and in 3 days killed 42,
lost none of their own.

1208
01:21:43,798 --> 01:21:46,392
<i>He does it with a fairly limited staff.</i>

1209
01:21:46,501 --> 01:21:49,834
Although some of his people,
like that young major there, Major Yuk--

1210
01:21:49,938 --> 01:21:51,838
tremendous guy.

1211
01:21:51,940 --> 01:21:55,467
He just heard his name over there.
Hey. [ Chuckles ]

1212
01:21:55,577 --> 01:21:58,239
[ Speaking Vietnamese ]

1213
01:22:14,896 --> 01:22:17,456
<i>It's no surprise</i>
<i>that in a very poor country...</i>

1214
01:22:17,565 --> 01:22:21,797
<i>you can find people</i>
<i>who will wear foreign uniforms.</i>

1215
01:22:21,903 --> 01:22:23,803
<i>What has always surprised us,</i>

1216
01:22:23,905 --> 01:22:27,807
<i>what we've never been willing</i>
<i>to predict or understand,</i>

1217
01:22:27,909 --> 01:22:30,810
is that the Vietnamese
communist leadership...

1218
01:22:30,912 --> 01:22:34,040
<i>can</i> find enough people
to live in the tunnels,

1219
01:22:34,149 --> 01:22:37,050
fight for nothing
wearing ragged shorts,

1220
01:22:37,152 --> 01:22:39,643
year after year
under the American bombs.

1221
01:22:39,754 --> 01:22:44,054
<i>A war in which one side</i>
<i>is entirely financed...</i>

1222
01:22:44,159 --> 01:22:47,151
<i>and equipped and supported</i>
<i>by foreigners...</i>

1223
01:22:47,262 --> 01:22:49,162
<i>is not a civil war.</i>

1224
01:22:49,264 --> 01:22:51,164
<i>The only foreigners</i>
<i>in that country...</i>

1225
01:22:51,266 --> 01:22:53,894
were the foreigners we financed
in the first part of the war...

1226
01:22:54,002 --> 01:22:58,905
and the foreigners we <i>were</i>
in the second half of the war.

1227
01:22:59,007 --> 01:23:01,407
Basically,
we didn't want to acknowledge...

1228
01:23:01,509 --> 01:23:03,409
the scale of our involvement there.

1229
01:23:03,511 --> 01:23:05,411
We didn't want to realize
that it was our war,

1230
01:23:05,513 --> 01:23:09,745
<i>because that would have been to say</i>
<i>that every casualty on both sides...</i>

1231
01:23:09,851 --> 01:23:12,342
<i>was a casualty</i>
<i>caused by our policy.</i>

1232
01:23:12,454 --> 01:23:16,322
The question used to be ''Might it
be possible we were on the wrong side...

1233
01:23:16,424 --> 01:23:18,722
in the Vietnamese War?''

1234
01:23:18,827 --> 01:23:21,261
We weren't on the wrong side.

1235
01:23:21,363 --> 01:23:24,059
We <i>are</i> the wrong side.

1236
01:23:30,105 --> 01:23:33,268
You have exemplified,
in your corner of the world,

1237
01:23:33,375 --> 01:23:35,536
patriotism of the highest order.

1238
01:23:35,643 --> 01:23:40,637
<i>You have brought to your great task</i>
<i>of organizing your country...</i>

1239
01:23:40,749 --> 01:23:44,207
<i>the greatest of courage,</i>
<i>the greatest of statesmanship.</i>

1240
01:23:49,924 --> 01:23:51,949
[ Speaking French ]

1241
01:23:55,330 --> 01:23:57,298
<i>[ Translator ]</i>
<i>I had two possibilities.</i>

1242
01:23:57,399 --> 01:24:00,630
<i>Either I could submit</i>
<i>to Washington's politics</i>--

1243
01:24:00,735 --> 01:24:03,898
Every morning, ''Yes, sir.''

1244
01:24:04,005 --> 01:24:06,530
<i>[ Translator ]</i>
<i>Or I would have to resign.</i>

1245
01:24:09,277 --> 01:24:13,043
<i>You can be sure that as a soldier</i>
<i>I only submit very rarely.</i>

1246
01:24:16,351 --> 01:24:18,319
<i>And, in fact, never.</i>

1247
01:24:18,420 --> 01:24:21,218
<i>I chose the second solution,</i>
<i>that of resigning.</i>

1248
01:24:21,322 --> 01:24:23,313
On the Vietnamese side,

1249
01:24:23,425 --> 01:24:26,155
I would say the most
encouraging factor...

1250
01:24:26,261 --> 01:24:29,025
is the promise offered
by General Khanh's government.

1251
01:24:29,130 --> 01:24:32,827
[ Speaking French ]

1252
01:24:32,934 --> 01:24:37,337
<i>[ Translator ] Through a security</i>
<i>service in the president's office,</i>

1253
01:24:37,439 --> 01:24:40,840
<i>we taped all communications</i>
<i>with the outside.</i>

1254
01:24:40,942 --> 01:24:44,343
<i>All telephone communications.</i>

1255
01:24:44,446 --> 01:24:48,348
<i>And fortunately, among these</i>
<i>taped telephone communications,</i>

1256
01:24:48,450 --> 01:24:51,851
<i>I still have the tape</i>
<i>from which we can hear precisely...</i>

1257
01:24:51,953 --> 01:24:53,978
<i>General Taylor...</i>

1258
01:24:56,524 --> 01:25:00,483
<i>stating precisely that he wants me,</i>
<i>General Khanh,</i>

1259
01:25:02,964 --> 01:25:05,364
<i>to leave Vietnam.</i>

1260
01:25:05,467 --> 01:25:08,595
-<i>[ Man ] Can you let us hear it?</i>
- [ Speaking French ]

1261
01:25:11,139 --> 01:25:13,437
<i>[ Translator ]</i>
<i>Certainly. I hope it works.</i>

1262
01:25:16,811 --> 01:25:20,042
- General Taylor.
- Uh, this is General Khanh speaking.

1263
01:25:20,148 --> 01:25:22,048
How are you?
Glad to hear you.

1264
01:25:22,150 --> 01:25:25,551
Uh, uh, may I speak in French?

1265
01:25:51,679 --> 01:25:54,011
Mr. President
and ladies and gentlemen,

1266
01:25:54,115 --> 01:25:56,413
as our joint communique indicates,

1267
01:25:56,518 --> 01:25:59,749
President Thieu and I have
had very constructive talks...

1268
01:25:59,854 --> 01:26:04,086
with regard to how we shall
work together in the years ahead,

1269
01:26:04,192 --> 01:26:08,424
working for the program of peace,

1270
01:26:08,530 --> 01:26:13,490
<i>which we now hope</i>
<i>will all be the wave of the future,</i>

1271
01:26:13,601 --> 01:26:16,764
<i>not only for the Republic of Vietnam,</i>

1272
01:26:16,871 --> 01:26:19,772
<i>but for all of the countries</i>
<i>in Indochina.</i>

1273
01:26:40,228 --> 01:26:43,095
<i>[ Man ] What kind of freedom</i>
<i>could you preserve here...</i>

1274
01:26:43,198 --> 01:26:47,965
<i>when you put so many</i>
<i>of our compatriots into prison...</i>

1275
01:26:48,069 --> 01:26:51,869
<i>without any charge,</i>
<i>without any reason why?</i>

1276
01:26:53,741 --> 01:26:57,973
Just because you want us
to have freedom?

1277
01:26:58,079 --> 01:27:01,640
What kind of freedom
could you give us?

1278
01:27:01,749 --> 01:27:05,651
We know that we only have freedom
if we fight for it.

1279
01:27:05,753 --> 01:27:09,553
But here we fight for what?

1280
01:27:09,657 --> 01:27:11,557
We fight for prisons?

1281
01:27:11,659 --> 01:27:14,127
[ Speaking French ]

1282
01:27:16,598 --> 01:27:20,728
<i>[ Translator ] People can be arrested</i>
<i>at any moment by any organization.</i>

1283
01:27:23,338 --> 01:27:27,297
<i>And then tortured in inhuman ways</i>
<i>in all the prisons.</i>

1284
01:27:28,543 --> 01:27:30,909
<i>And, above all, in police stations.</i>

1285
01:27:35,183 --> 01:27:38,710
<i>And then imprisoned</i>
<i>for years and years without trial.</i>

1286
01:27:39,854 --> 01:27:41,913
<i>Their only crime</i>
<i>is loving their country.</i>

1287
01:27:44,292 --> 01:27:47,523
<i>They had the courage</i>
<i>to tell the truth.</i>

1288
01:27:47,629 --> 01:27:50,860
<i>They asked for the liberation</i>
<i>of political prisoners.</i>

1289
01:27:53,301 --> 01:27:55,599
<i>They asked for an end to the war.</i>

1290
01:27:57,105 --> 01:28:01,201
<i>They asked for peace,</i>
<i>for national reconciliation.</i>

1291
01:28:01,309 --> 01:28:05,746
<i>And all that is considered a crime</i>
<i>by the government of Thieu.</i>

1292
01:28:06,914 --> 01:28:09,883
[ Speaking Vietnamese ]

1293
01:28:12,053 --> 01:28:14,817
<i>[ Translator ]</i>
<i>I was arrested in 1 968.</i>

1294
01:28:14,922 --> 01:28:17,948
I was at home
when the security police came.

1295
01:28:19,327 --> 01:28:22,319
<i>They took me to headquarters</i>
<i>for a few questions...</i>

1296
01:28:22,430 --> 01:28:24,455
<i>and kept me.</i>

1297
01:28:30,071 --> 01:28:33,734
<i>You can't imagine</i>
<i>how badly I was beaten.</i>

1298
01:28:33,841 --> 01:28:37,504
<i>Mostly on the head.</i>
<i>My eyes are bad now.</i>

1299
01:28:37,612 --> 01:28:41,070
<i>After I was arrested,</i>
<i>I was beaten so badly...</i>

1300
01:28:41,182 --> 01:28:43,275
<i>even now</i>
<i>I sometimes have headaches...</i>

1301
01:28:43,384 --> 01:28:45,682
<i>and nosebleeds and ear-bleeds.</i>

1302
01:28:49,524 --> 01:28:53,187
<i>In those days, all we were</i>
<i>getting to eat was rotten fish,</i>

1303
01:28:53,294 --> 01:28:55,592
<i>so we asked</i>
<i>for some vegetables.</i>

1304
01:28:55,697 --> 01:28:58,495
<i>But when we complained,</i>
<i>we were beaten and chained...</i>

1305
01:28:58,599 --> 01:29:00,760
<i>and lime powder</i>
<i>was thrown on us.</i>

1306
01:29:00,868 --> 01:29:04,326
<i>And they poured water on us,</i>
<i>and we had nowhere to run.</i>

1307
01:29:09,811 --> 01:29:12,109
<i>Our cells were this big...</i>

1308
01:29:12,213 --> 01:29:14,943
<i>and we could do nothing</i>
<i>but stand where we were...</i>

1309
01:29:15,049 --> 01:29:17,779
<i>and get the water</i>
<i>and the lime all over us.</i>

1310
01:29:17,885 --> 01:29:20,786
<i>Some of us lost our teeth</i>
<i>and our hair.</i>

1311
01:29:20,888 --> 01:29:25,291
<i>And when the lime got wet,</i>
<i>it just boiled up, bubbling all over us.</i>

1312
01:29:25,393 --> 01:29:30,353
<i>Our hair fell out and our skin</i>
<i>became covered with sores.</i>

1313
01:29:33,735 --> 01:29:36,295
<i>They said that</i>
<i>if we were innocent,</i>

1314
01:29:36,404 --> 01:29:39,305
<i>they would beat us</i>
<i>until we were guilty,</i>

1315
01:29:39,407 --> 01:29:41,568
<i>and that if we were guilty,</i>

1316
01:29:41,676 --> 01:29:44,144
<i>they would beat us</i>
<i>until we repent.</i>

1317
01:29:50,151 --> 01:29:55,987
In a country where the people
don't hold national sovereignty,

1318
01:29:56,090 --> 01:29:59,526
in a country where
the government has proven itself...

1319
01:29:59,627 --> 01:30:01,652
to be the enemy of the people,

1320
01:30:01,763 --> 01:30:04,197
the prisoners are the patriots.

1321
01:30:04,298 --> 01:30:06,198
[ Breathing Heavily ]

1322
01:30:06,300 --> 01:30:09,326
And no matter
how badly treated we are,

1323
01:30:09,437 --> 01:30:12,736
still we are proud,

1324
01:30:12,840 --> 01:30:14,774
because at least we are free,

1325
01:30:14,876 --> 01:30:20,075
instead of enslaved as so many
of the so-called government officials.

1326
01:30:20,181 --> 01:30:22,342
[ Speaking French ]

1327
01:30:24,519 --> 01:30:26,419
<i>[ Translator ]</i>
<i>And so,you see,</i>

1328
01:30:26,521 --> 01:30:29,422
<i>when a Vietnamese works</i>
<i>for peace and for liberty,</i>

1329
01:30:31,058 --> 01:30:33,424
<i>he is considered a communist.</i>

1330
01:30:37,965 --> 01:30:42,265
<i>It is an honor for the communists</i>
<i>to have to work for peace and justice.</i>

1331
01:30:44,906 --> 01:30:48,706
<i>So it is the government which</i>
<i>gives validity to being a communist,</i>

1332
01:30:48,810 --> 01:30:50,710
<i>because they continue to say...</i>

1333
01:30:50,812 --> 01:30:54,771
<i>that the people who work forjustice</i>
<i>and for peace are communists.</i>

1334
01:30:56,617 --> 01:30:58,517
<i>You see?</i>

1335
01:30:58,619 --> 01:31:00,746
<i>[ Coker ]</i>
<i>We were learning to be good soldiers...</i>

1336
01:31:00,855 --> 01:31:02,789
<i>back when you're three, four,</i>
<i>five, six years old.</i>

1337
01:31:02,890 --> 01:31:07,224
<i>That's when good ol'mom is telling you</i>
<i>to obey the local camp regulations.</i>

1338
01:31:07,328 --> 01:31:09,626
In this case, it's the house.

1339
01:31:09,730 --> 01:31:13,063
And you start to learn
to respect authority.

1340
01:31:13,167 --> 01:31:16,068
And so, finally, lo and behold,
at 20, 22 years old,

1341
01:31:16,170 --> 01:31:20,231
you find yourself in service
and maybe take that last and final step,

1342
01:31:20,341 --> 01:31:22,741
where you become
quite regimented...

1343
01:31:22,844 --> 01:31:25,404
in a military form of discipline.

1344
01:31:25,513 --> 01:31:29,916
That stuff isn't worth the paper it's
written on, if the basis isn't there.

1345
01:31:30,017 --> 01:31:33,453
You need that cornerstone that goes back
to childhood, and who's teaching you,

1346
01:31:33,554 --> 01:31:38,048
<i>but good old moms,</i>
<i>women like yourselves.</i>

1347
01:31:38,159 --> 01:31:41,424
<i>It's terrifying. When you're facing</i>
<i>a torture session with a bunch of gooks,</i>

1348
01:31:41,529 --> 01:31:43,429
it's gonna be pretty darn miserable.

1349
01:31:43,531 --> 01:31:45,761
No doubt about it.
You're scared. You're really petrified.

1350
01:31:45,867 --> 01:31:48,768
But at the other side,
you have a bunch of women back there...

1351
01:31:48,870 --> 01:31:51,430
telling you, ''You better do something,''
you know?

1352
01:31:51,539 --> 01:31:54,770
That's the wrath of God. You don't
want 1 00 women climbing down your back,

1353
01:31:54,876 --> 01:31:57,470
-<i>[ Laughter ]</i>
- So you figure the gooks aren't so bad.

1354
01:31:57,578 --> 01:31:59,512
<i>So you press on.</i>

1355
01:31:59,614 --> 01:32:02,276
<i>In many respects,</i>
<i>the destiny of our country,</i>

1356
01:32:02,383 --> 01:32:05,614
<i>and more personally,</i>
<i>the destiny of me,</i>

1357
01:32:05,720 --> 01:32:08,120
<i>your men,your children...</i>

1358
01:32:08,222 --> 01:32:10,452
<i>is in your hands.</i>

1359
01:32:10,558 --> 01:32:13,959
<i>If you are proud of the P.O. W.s</i>
<i>and personally of me,</i>

1360
01:32:14,061 --> 01:32:16,291
then you should be
proud of yourselves,

1361
01:32:16,397 --> 01:32:19,389
because I was
what you made me to be.

1362
01:32:19,500 --> 01:32:21,400
As for my own view,

1363
01:32:21,502 --> 01:32:23,868
uh, I thought through
as best I could...

1364
01:32:23,971 --> 01:32:26,963
the meaning of Southeast Asia
to the United States in the 1 950s,

1365
01:32:27,074 --> 01:32:29,304
looking backward
and looking forward...

1366
01:32:29,410 --> 01:32:32,971
in terms of what I know about
the dynamics of societies and so on.

1367
01:32:33,080 --> 01:32:36,015
And on balance--
It is an on-balance judgment--

1368
01:32:36,117 --> 01:32:38,984
I came to the judgment that it's
a vital interest to the United States.

1369
01:32:39,086 --> 01:32:41,554
I've never had any reason
to change that judgment.

1370
01:32:43,257 --> 01:32:47,626
And, uh, therefore, I, uh,

1371
01:32:47,728 --> 01:32:52,062
I do believe that what we have done
is generally right,

1372
01:32:52,166 --> 01:32:55,795
although I would have preferred
to have seen a different,

1373
01:32:55,903 --> 01:32:57,928
more decisive military strategy.

1374
01:32:58,039 --> 01:33:00,337
Certainly, to me,

1375
01:33:00,441 --> 01:33:05,105
the day you can say that a sacrifice
such as that is not worthwhile...

1376
01:33:05,212 --> 01:33:07,840
is the day that you've destroyed
all your real values...

1377
01:33:07,949 --> 01:33:10,440
of what is worthwhile
and what isn't.

1378
01:33:10,551 --> 01:33:12,451
And there's no question in my mind...

1379
01:33:12,553 --> 01:33:16,011
that he and everybody else
that did what he did--

1380
01:33:16,123 --> 01:33:18,853
there's no sacrifice that is in vain.

1381
01:33:18,960 --> 01:33:23,863
Absolutely none. Down the line,
that's the price you pay for freedom...

1382
01:33:23,965 --> 01:33:29,028
and that's the price that you pay
for the kind of stature that we have...

1383
01:33:29,136 --> 01:33:31,229
and it's the kind of risk you take...

1384
01:33:31,339 --> 01:33:33,773
to preserve the ideals that we have.

1385
01:33:33,874 --> 01:33:35,774
He had just a tremendous
sense of humor...

1386
01:33:35,876 --> 01:33:41,542
and just an amazing, instinctive sense
of what was important and what wasn't.

1387
01:33:41,649 --> 01:33:44,709
I remember when I was getting ready
for our oldest daughter's wedding,

1388
01:33:44,819 --> 01:33:47,879
and I was upset because
something or other wasn't going well,

1389
01:33:47,989 --> 01:33:51,288
and he called up from Pensacola
and he said, ''How are thing's going?''

1390
01:33:51,392 --> 01:33:53,952
And I said, ''Fine, Bing,
but such-and-such has happened.''

1391
01:33:54,061 --> 01:33:56,962
He said, ''Oh, Mom,
don't sweat the small stuff.''

1392
01:33:57,064 --> 01:33:59,225
[ Laughs ] You know,
it just made all the difference.

1393
01:33:59,333 --> 01:34:02,063
I thought, ''Gee. That really
is small stuff, you know?''

1394
01:34:02,169 --> 01:34:04,228
And it was. Yeah.

1395
01:34:04,338 --> 01:34:06,863
And it made the whole thing
much easier.

1396
01:34:06,974 --> 01:34:11,570
<i>And, of course, I came up in a tradition</i>
<i>where military service was</i>--

1397
01:34:11,679 --> 01:34:14,910
In World War II, there was no question
everybody was part of it.

1398
01:34:15,016 --> 01:34:17,507
There was not the kind
of dissension and so forth...

1399
01:34:17,618 --> 01:34:22,112
that there has been surrounding
the Vietnam thing.

1400
01:34:22,223 --> 01:34:24,748
<i>But I think that most of the people</i>
<i>of this country...</i>

1401
01:34:24,859 --> 01:34:27,589
are too busy
to get involved deeply...

1402
01:34:27,695 --> 01:34:29,595
<i>in, uh, uh,</i>

1403
01:34:29,697 --> 01:34:33,599
<i>on, uh, the kind of things</i>
<i>that the dissenters do.</i>

1404
01:34:33,701 --> 01:34:36,670
<i>In other words, I think that really</i>
<i>the strength of our system,</i>

1405
01:34:36,771 --> 01:34:38,864
and I think it's a terrific system,

1406
01:34:38,973 --> 01:34:43,376
is that you do rely on somebody
like President Nixon for leadership.

1407
01:34:43,477 --> 01:34:48,608
I think his team of people with him
are outstanding...

1408
01:34:48,716 --> 01:34:51,776
and, to me,
the leadership that he has shown...

1409
01:34:51,886 --> 01:34:54,286
and decisions
that he has made,

1410
01:34:54,388 --> 01:34:59,291
uh, really have--
They're the kind of decisions...

1411
01:34:59,393 --> 01:35:01,793
I would expect from
the president of this country.

1412
01:35:01,896 --> 01:35:05,388
And the action he has taken
is the action I'd expect...

1413
01:35:05,499 --> 01:35:07,797
from the president of this country.

1414
01:35:07,902 --> 01:35:11,963
I think the whole executive,

1415
01:35:12,073 --> 01:35:17,978
legislative and judicial system
that we have is superb.

1416
01:35:18,079 --> 01:35:22,812
It has worked many, many-- far better
than any other system I'm aware of...

1417
01:35:22,917 --> 01:35:26,478
and brought us
to our state of power...

1418
01:35:26,587 --> 01:35:31,650
and, uh, really,
of international stature...

1419
01:35:31,759 --> 01:35:37,595
that we have a responsibility
to stay with and to uphold.

1420
01:35:37,698 --> 01:35:40,565
[ Clears Throat ]

1421
01:35:40,668 --> 01:35:43,000
<i>[ Man ] What did your son</i>
<i>want to become?</i>

1422
01:35:43,104 --> 01:35:45,902
<i>I suspect he would have</i>
<i>gone into the newspaper.</i>

1423
01:35:46,006 --> 01:35:49,169
He actually had just got a job
with <i>the New York Times...</i>

1424
01:35:49,276 --> 01:35:54,373
when he went
into the, uh, O.C.S.

1425
01:35:55,616 --> 01:36:00,019
And he'd worked for newspapers
in the summer...

1426
01:36:00,121 --> 01:36:02,988
while he was at college.

1427
01:36:06,127 --> 01:36:08,687
<i>I suppose that</i>
<i>it's like any pain.</i>

1428
01:36:08,796 --> 01:36:12,755
You don't remember pain too well...
afterwards.

1429
01:36:14,034 --> 01:36:17,003
[ ''Thanks For The Memories'' ]

1430
01:36:19,907 --> 01:36:22,375
<i>[ Applause ]</i>

1431
01:36:30,751 --> 01:36:34,653
<i>Thank you. Thank you very much,</i>
<i>Mr. President, dear people.</i>

1432
01:36:34,755 --> 01:36:38,384
<i>I'm thrilled to be here with you guys.</i>
<i>This is what I like</i>--<i>a captive audience.</i>

1433
01:36:38,492 --> 01:36:40,619
<i>[ Laughter ]</i>

1434
01:36:42,329 --> 01:36:44,354
<i>[ Scattered Boos, Groans ]</i>

1435
01:36:45,866 --> 01:36:48,391
It is always the custom
at a dinner at the White House...

1436
01:36:48,502 --> 01:36:51,835
to have a toast
to the honored guest.

1437
01:36:51,939 --> 01:36:54,840
The difficulty tonight is that
there are so many honored guests...

1438
01:36:54,942 --> 01:36:57,570
that we would be drinking
all night and into the day.

1439
01:36:57,678 --> 01:37:00,647
<i>[ Cheering, Applause ]</i>

1440
01:37:05,352 --> 01:37:08,378
Somebody just said,
''What's wrong with that?''

1441
01:37:10,057 --> 01:37:12,958
<i>The most difficult decision that</i>
<i>I have made since being president...</i>

1442
01:37:13,060 --> 01:37:16,257
was on December the 1 8th of last year.

1443
01:37:16,363 --> 01:37:18,331
- [ Cheering, Applause ]
- There--

1444
01:37:18,432 --> 01:37:22,698
<i>[ Applause Continues ]</i>

1445
01:37:25,940 --> 01:37:27,805
<i>And there were many occasions...</i>

1446
01:37:27,908 --> 01:37:30,741
<i>in the 1 0-day period</i>
<i>after the decision was made...</i>

1447
01:37:30,845 --> 01:37:33,780
<i>when I wondered whether</i>
<i>this country really supported it.</i>

1448
01:37:33,881 --> 01:37:36,042
<i>But I can tell you this:</i>

1449
01:37:36,150 --> 01:37:40,951
<i>After having met each one</i>
<i>of our honored guests this evening...</i>

1450
01:37:41,055 --> 01:37:43,285
and after having talked to them,

1451
01:37:43,390 --> 01:37:46,450
I think that all of us...

1452
01:37:46,560 --> 01:37:48,790
would like to join
in a round of applause...

1453
01:37:48,896 --> 01:37:53,128
for the brave men that
took those B-52s in and did the job.

1454
01:37:53,234 --> 01:37:56,203
<i>[ Cheering, Applause ]</i>

1455
01:38:03,110 --> 01:38:06,170
<i>[ Cheering, Applause Continues ]</i>

1456
01:38:17,057 --> 01:38:19,787
[ Bombs Whistling ]

1457
01:38:58,933 --> 01:39:00,924
<i>[ Wind Whistling ]</i>

1458
01:39:01,035 --> 01:39:03,503
<i>[ Fires Crackling ]</i>

1459
01:39:18,953 --> 01:39:20,853
[ Speaking Vietnamese ]

1460
01:39:20,955 --> 01:39:23,446
<i>[ Translator ]</i>
<i>My eight-year-old daughter was killed.</i>

1461
01:39:24,992 --> 01:39:27,552
<i>And my three-year-old son.</i>

1462
01:39:27,661 --> 01:39:30,630
<i>[ Man ]</i>
<i>A son, three years old, killed.</i>

1463
01:39:33,000 --> 01:39:35,468
<i>[ Translator ]</i>
<i>Nixon, murderer of civilians.</i>

1464
01:39:37,338 --> 01:39:41,399
<i>What have I done to Nixon so that</i>
<i>he comes here to bomb my country?</i>

1465
01:39:43,043 --> 01:39:45,910
<i>My daughter died right here.</i>

1466
01:39:46,013 --> 01:39:48,481
<i>She was feeding the pigs.</i>

1467
01:39:48,582 --> 01:39:50,516
<i>She was so sweet.</i>

1468
01:39:52,186 --> 01:39:55,587
<i>She is dead.</i>
<i>The pigs are alive.</i>

1469
01:39:57,358 --> 01:40:00,919
<i>My mother and my children</i>
<i>took shelter here.</i>

1470
01:40:01,028 --> 01:40:02,996
Here they died.

1471
01:40:07,534 --> 01:40:09,593
<i>The planes came from over there.</i>

1472
01:40:09,703 --> 01:40:11,603
<i>No targets here.</i>

1473
01:40:11,705 --> 01:40:14,003
<i>Only rice fields and houses.</i>

1474
01:40:15,509 --> 01:40:18,774
<i>I'll give you</i>
<i>my daughter's beautiful shirt.</i>

1475
01:40:20,547 --> 01:40:23,015
<i>Take it back</i>
<i>to the United States.</i>

1476
01:40:24,551 --> 01:40:26,678
<i>Tell them what happened here.</i>

1477
01:40:26,787 --> 01:40:29,017
<i>My daughter is dead.</i>

1478
01:40:30,391 --> 01:40:32,689
<i>She will never wear the shirt again.</i>

1479
01:40:37,998 --> 01:40:40,364
<i>Throw the shirt in Nixon's face.</i>

1480
01:40:42,069 --> 01:40:46,369
<i>Tell them she was only</i>
<i>a little schoolgirl.</i>

1481
01:40:48,675 --> 01:40:51,644
[ Sobbing ]

1482
01:40:58,552 --> 01:41:01,020
[ Sobbing Continues ]

1483
01:41:08,062 --> 01:41:10,360
[ Sobbing ]

1484
01:41:19,606 --> 01:41:21,574
[ Wailing ]

1485
01:41:29,650 --> 01:41:32,619
<i>[ Prayer Drum Tapping ]</i>

1486
01:41:39,526 --> 01:41:42,495
[ Men Speaking Vietnamese ]

1487
